Flight from Moscow
The downfall of communism gave the nations of the former Soviet bloc the opportunity to turn towards democracy, market economics, and the rule of law.
Some of these countries decisively broke ties with their communist past; others were less successful, and a few have catastrophically failed.
Moldova and Georgia belonged to the latter category until recently.
Their economic and political failure was largely based on secessionist movements, supported by Russia, that sought to keep both countries within the "sphere of influence" of the Kremlin.
As bloody conflicts erupted in Transnistria, Abkhazia, and South Ossetia, Russia transformed its military presence there into "peacekeeping troops" to maintain control.
Long had one feared that these so-called "frozen conflicts" could suddenly turn into hot ones.
Not only has this not happened, but we can now speak of solutions – because both Georgia and Moldova have begun to make a breakthrough towards market economics and democracy.
To this end, the European Union's "Neighbourhood Policy" has also contributed.
The starting point of these developments was the "Rose Revolution" in Georgia three years ago.
Having already been perilously close to a failed state, Georgia has meanwhile turned towards the West.
The success of various "colour revolutions" in former Soviet bloc countries also triggered change in Moldova. Here, President Vladimir Voronin initiated reforms aimed at drawing closer to the EU.
These changes have triggered new initiatives in Georgia and Moldova to restore the territorial integrity of these countries in a peaceful manner.
The experience of Estonia suggests how Georgia and Moldova should shape their policy towards Russia.
When Estonia gained independence in 1991, Moscow sought to portray Estonia as an economy with enormous problems, unsuitable for investment.
Estonia was indeed poor, and its main export products were scrap metal and wood, but its economy was growing.
In northeast Estonia, with its predominantly ethnic Russian population, which had settled here during the Soviet era, Russia supported a so-called "autonomy movement".
When Estonia resisted, Russia imposed sanctions and cut off gas supplies.
When only a few Estonian products were allowed to be imported into Russia, high taxes were levied on them, and Russia even threatened with a military intervention.
But Estonia kept its cool.
When Russia imposed sanctions, the country even managed to redirect its economy towards the West.
Western Europe, on the other hand, did its best to integrate the Baltic states – Lithuania, Latvia, and Estonia – and at the same time sought to avoid a conflict with Russia.
In 1994, an EU trade agreement enabled Estonian products to find new markets, ultimately making Estonia one of the most successful post-communist transition countries, and it joined the EU and NATO in 2004.
When Georgia gained independence in 1991, it did not receive similar support from Western Europe.
Georgia appeared less attractive as a partner than the Baltic states; the 1990s were marked by coups, counter-coups, and civil wars, with two regions – Abkhazia and South Ossetia – essentially seceding with Russia's support.
The country has done its best to put its bleak past behind it.
Since der Rose Revolution wurde die Wirtschaft reformiert, die Armee gestärkt, und die Führung des Landes ist jung, dynamisch und eifrig bemüht, das Land voranzubringen.
Thanks to Georgia's flat income tax rate of 12% – likely the lowest in the world – the national budget has increased.
The government has raised pensions and increased social benefits.
Corruption is decreasing, and a justice reform has been initiated.
The economy grew by 8% in 2005 and by over 10% in 2006.
Georgia is making efforts to ease tensions over Abkhazia and South Ossetia; however, Russia accuses the country of aggression and ethnic cleansing.
His main goal is to prevent the West from supporting Georgia and block reconciliation with the breakaway regions.
The powers that matter in Georgia are Russia and the United States to a certain extent.
Europe must show that it is equally important.
Estonia has shown, in its independence and again during the recent crisis over the relocation of a monument from the Soviet era, that it can resist Russian pressure with determination and strong support.
Europe must understand that Georgia needs trade, not humanitarian aid.
Just as the free trade agreement with Europe enabled Estonia to find new markets, this can be the means by which the Georgians help themselves.
Georgia has just cause to hope that it will achieve genuine independence. But what about Moldova, the poorest country in Europe, which is more threatened by Russia than Estonia or even Georgia ever were?
The missing reform achievements are partly the result of the secessionist movements supported by Russia.
That the industrialized region of Transnistria – whose Russian- and Ukrainian-speaking population feared that the majority of Moldovans of Romanian descent planned closer ties with Romania – seceded from Moldova dealt the country's independence a severe blow from the very start.
A civil war followed, and in 1992 Russian troops marched into Transnistria, where they remain to this day.
Transnistria's independence was never recognized – neither by Moldova nor internationally.
It is said that there is lawlessness and corruption there.
Moldova is heavily indebted, unemployment is high, and its once-renowned wine industry is in decline.
Russia occasionally cuts off gas supplies, and many of the country's four million citizens have left the country.
Only Russia can solve this problem.
Government representatives of Moldova have made four unsuccessful visits to Moscow to persuade President Vladimir Putin to seek a solution and withdraw Russian troops.
A desperate Voronin has appealed to the EU monitoring mission EUBAM for help, but a EU initiative would require Russian cooperation.
Unfortunately, it seems that the West lacks current insights into the situation in Moldova.
In April, for instance, the EU and the US learned about a proposed peace agreement only through a leaked report from Germany.
This appears to favor Russia, as Moldova would be required to recognize Transnistria as a legitimate entity.
If Russia has thus outmaneuvered the West, this would be a dire precedent for Georgia and other weak post-communist states.
